WEBVTT
Kind: captions
Language: en

00:00:01.510 --> 00:00:04.311
Prof: Okay,
so I want to continue the story

00:00:04.311 --> 00:00:07.226
about cleaning up landscapes
that have been severely

00:00:07.226 --> 00:00:07.970
affected.
 

00:00:07.970 --> 00:00:12.800
And I wanted to use this as a
basis for reviewing a variety of

00:00:12.800 --> 00:00:17.393
different laws that apply and
certain key provisions in the

00:00:17.393 --> 00:00:21.590
statutes that have met with more
or less success.

00:00:21.590 --> 00:00:26.865
And I'm going to start today
with the National Environmental

00:00:26.865 --> 00:00:30.800
Policy Act, which was passed in
late 1969.

00:00:30.800 --> 00:00:34.309
And it was one of the first
statutes that declared a

00:00:34.309 --> 00:00:38.370
comprehensive national policy to
protect the environment.

00:00:38.370 --> 00:00:42.242
And I wanted to just pause on
this, because many people think

00:00:42.242 --> 00:00:45.340
that the idea of sustainability
is fairly new.

00:00:45.340 --> 00:00:48.510
But if you look at the purpose
statement inside this statute,

00:00:48.510 --> 00:00:52.046
you see that back in the late
1960s that many of the ideals

00:00:52.046 --> 00:00:55.279
that people now believe and
think of when they use the

00:00:55.279 --> 00:00:59.060
phrase sustainability are deeply
embedded in this statute.

00:00:59.060 --> 00:01:02.060
So let me just go through this
quickly.

00:01:02.060 --> 00:01:04.674
"The Congress,
recognizing the profound impact

00:01:04.674 --> 00:01:07.605
of man's activity on the
interrelations of all components

00:01:07.605 --> 00:01:10.906
of the natural environment,
particularly the profound

00:01:10.906 --> 00:01:14.982
influences of population growth,
high-density urbanization,

00:01:14.982 --> 00:01:17.950
industrial expansion,
resource exploitation,

00:01:17.950 --> 00:01:20.769
and new and expanding
technological advances,

00:01:20.769 --> 00:01:24.418
and recognizing further the
critical importance of restoring

00:01:24.418 --> 00:01:28.067
and maintaining environmental
quality to the overall welfare

00:01:28.067 --> 00:01:31.099
and development of man,
declares that it is the

00:01:31.099 --> 00:01:33.700
continuing policy of the federal
government,

00:01:33.700 --> 00:01:36.938
in cooperation with state and
local governments and other

00:01:36.938 --> 00:01:39.599
concerned public and private
organizations,

00:01:39.599 --> 00:01:42.410
to use all practicable means
and measures,

00:01:42.410 --> 00:01:45.765
including financial and
technical assistance in a manner

00:01:45.765 --> 00:01:49.120
calculated to foster and promote
the general welfare.

00:01:49.120 --> 00:01:52.253
To create and maintain
conditions under which man and

00:01:52.253 --> 00:01:56.170
nature can exist in productive
harmony and fulfill the social,

00:01:56.170 --> 00:01:58.250
economic, and other
requirements of present and

00:01:58.250 --> 00:02:00.060
future generations of
Americans."

00:02:00.060 --> 00:02:04.680
This is an exceptionally broad
mission statement.

00:02:04.680 --> 00:02:07.790
This law was passed,
not with any regulatory

00:02:07.790 --> 00:02:11.770
authority, so it could not
prevent human development.

00:02:11.770 --> 00:02:15.628
But it demanded instead that
any project,

00:02:15.628 --> 00:02:21.616
private or federal,
that would receive public funds

00:02:21.616 --> 00:02:26.877
from the Federal Treasury,
would be required to declare

00:02:26.877 --> 00:02:30.388
exactly what the proposed
development was and to project

00:02:30.388 --> 00:02:33.643
out what the environmental
effects might be into the

00:02:33.643 --> 00:02:34.410
future.
 

00:02:34.410 --> 00:02:38.342
The statute was also curious in
that it included something

00:02:38.342 --> 00:02:40.690
called a citizen suit provision.
 

00:02:40.690 --> 00:02:44.831
So that environmental groups or
other citizen watchdog groups

00:02:44.831 --> 00:02:49.607
could monitor federal agencies,
they could look at their budget

00:02:49.607 --> 00:02:54.306
and think about what kinds of
development were being proposed

00:02:54.306 --> 00:02:57.468
by Congress,
contained in authorization

00:02:57.468 --> 00:03:01.717
statutes or appropriations,
and then think down the road

00:03:01.717 --> 00:03:06.104
about how to make sure that
those developments proceeded in

00:03:06.104 --> 00:03:10.188
a way that had a minimal impact
on the environment.

00:03:10.188 --> 00:03:13.641
So this was the origin of the
idea of an environmental impact

00:03:13.641 --> 00:03:17.409
statement,
a model for declaring and

00:03:17.409 --> 00:03:24.538
basically making public all
proposals for new development.

00:03:24.538 --> 00:03:27.616
And also, it created an
enormous industry in the

00:03:27.616 --> 00:03:31.555
environmental sciences,
an industry that really

00:03:31.555 --> 00:03:35.542
involved soil scientists,
atmospheric chemists,

00:03:35.542 --> 00:03:39.566
water quality experts that all
joined together to try to figure

00:03:39.566 --> 00:03:43.460
out exactly what the effects of
new development might be.

00:03:43.460 --> 00:03:47.241
Now, if you think about the
scale of our economy and you

00:03:47.241 --> 00:03:51.367
think about the federal budget
and you realize that just this

00:03:51.367 --> 00:03:55.220
past week our president issued
his proposed budget,

00:03:55.220 --> 00:03:56.740
almost $3 trillion.
 

00:03:56.740 --> 00:04:01.508
That's an enormous amount of
money being expended that would

00:04:01.508 --> 00:04:06.360
be put into projects developed
by the Defense Department,

00:04:06.360 --> 00:04:08.461
the Energy Department,
the Department of

00:04:08.461 --> 00:04:10.080
Transportation and Highways.
 

00:04:10.080 --> 00:04:12.139
Even the Environmental
Protection Agency,

00:04:12.139 --> 00:04:15.425
when they issue a permit now to
a new sewage treatment plant or

00:04:15.425 --> 00:04:18.699
a new water supply facility,
that treatment plant must be

00:04:18.699 --> 00:04:22.310
reviewed in the context of an
environmental impact statement.

00:04:22.310 --> 00:04:25.577
So that any expenditure of
funds demands that this

00:04:25.577 --> 00:04:27.980
forward-looking projection
occur,

00:04:27.980 --> 00:04:31.509
and it's always open to citizen
suit,

00:04:31.509 --> 00:04:33.730
citizen contest through
litigation.

00:04:33.730 --> 00:04:38.410
And it's been very effective in
altering new development.

00:04:38.410 --> 00:04:41.440
Many dams have been stopped by
this statute,

00:04:41.440 --> 00:04:44.598
by judges' interpretation of
it, because of claims of

00:04:44.598 --> 00:04:47.940
insufficiency of the
environmental impact statements.

00:04:47.940 --> 00:04:53.213
So that it also includes a very
extensive public hearing process

00:04:53.213 --> 00:04:56.310
whereby drafts have to be
prepared.

00:04:56.310 --> 00:04:58.629
They have to be taken to public
hearing,

00:04:58.629 --> 00:05:00.740
people have to have an
opportunity to review the

00:05:00.740 --> 00:05:02.942
material so that they can
understand what might be

00:05:02.942 --> 00:05:04.379
happening in their backyard.
 

00:05:04.379 --> 00:05:08.836
And they may also be very
critical of the quality of

00:05:08.836 --> 00:05:09.709
science.
 

00:05:09.709 --> 00:05:13.577
And this is not laboratory
science, this is science that

00:05:13.577 --> 00:05:15.899
really is predictive in nature.
 

00:05:15.899 --> 00:05:18.370
It's probabilistic in a sense.
 

00:05:18.370 --> 00:05:23.560
So most environmental science
that demands forecasting,

00:05:23.560 --> 00:05:26.459
you should think about it as
being probabilistic,

00:05:26.459 --> 00:05:30.499
which is why most programs in
environmental studies have a

00:05:30.499 --> 00:05:33.476
requirement for taking
statistics and often

00:05:33.476 --> 00:05:34.610
probability.
 

00:05:34.610 --> 00:05:38.449
So the scientists needed to
look into the past and try to

00:05:38.449 --> 00:05:42.495
discern from previous studies
what was most likely to happen

00:05:42.495 --> 00:05:43.730
in the future.
 

00:05:43.730 --> 00:05:47.899
And the only way that a project
could be stopped would be if the

00:05:47.899 --> 00:05:51.209
impact statement were found to
be insufficient,

00:05:51.209 --> 00:05:54.711
to not fully have disclosed
what the effects would be or to

00:05:54.711 --> 00:05:57.550
include science that really was
poorly done,

00:05:57.550 --> 00:06:00.889
that did not seem defensible.
 

00:06:00.889 --> 00:06:05.170
So I'm going to move on to
discuss several other statutes

00:06:05.170 --> 00:06:05.629
now.
 

00:06:05.629 --> 00:06:08.495
But one key point is that
citizen suit provisions have

00:06:08.495 --> 00:06:11.579
been built into a variety of
major environmental laws,

00:06:11.579 --> 00:06:14.480
including the Clean Air Act,
the Clean Water Act,

00:06:14.480 --> 00:06:16.589
CERCLA, which is the Superfund
law,

00:06:16.589 --> 00:06:19.180
the Resource Conservation and
Recovery Act,

00:06:19.180 --> 00:06:21.500
the cradle-to-grave statute
that I mentioned the other day,

00:06:21.500 --> 00:06:24.930
the Emergency Planning and
Community Right to Know Act,

00:06:24.930 --> 00:06:28.964
which gives communities the
right to know what chemicals are

00:06:28.964 --> 00:06:32.656
being released in their
environments if those chemicals

00:06:32.656 --> 00:06:35.870
are recognized to be hazardous
substances,

00:06:35.870 --> 00:06:38.620
and the Endangered Species Act.
 

00:06:38.620 --> 00:06:42.084
So basically,
this opportunity for litigation

00:06:42.084 --> 00:06:46.807
has really radically changed the
way that new development and

00:06:46.807 --> 00:06:50.430
uses of the environment have
gone forward.

00:06:50.430 --> 00:06:52.982
Now in this case,
in the case that we talked

00:06:52.982 --> 00:06:56.449
about on Tuesday,
hazardous site on Vieques in

00:06:56.449 --> 00:07:00.396
Puerto Rico,
this was a very important

00:07:00.396 --> 00:07:06.223
statute in that the court case,
Romero-Barcelo v.

00:07:06.223 --> 00:07:10.579
Weinberger,
or Weinberger v.

00:07:10.579 --> 00:07:14.322
Romero-Barcelo,
was brought in part because the

00:07:14.322 --> 00:07:18.206
Navy had not developed an
environmental impact statement

00:07:18.206 --> 00:07:22.161
that projected out what the
long-term effects might be of

00:07:22.161 --> 00:07:25.269
their continued bombing of the
island.

00:07:25.269 --> 00:07:30.564
So this statute required-- was
interpreted by a judge in Puerto

00:07:30.564 --> 00:07:35.858
Rico to require the development
of a draft environmental impact

00:07:35.858 --> 00:07:38.240
statement,
which was prepared.

00:07:38.240 --> 00:07:39.886
It's kind of curious,
because I wanted to find that

00:07:39.886 --> 00:07:41.170
draft environmental impact
statement.

00:07:41.170 --> 00:07:44.735
I didn't know whether or not
there might be projections of

00:07:44.735 --> 00:07:48.300
long-term damage or perhaps
accounting of kinds of weapons

00:07:48.300 --> 00:07:49.990
that had been released.
 

00:07:49.990 --> 00:07:53.399
So I looked for it and in Mudd
Library,

00:07:53.399 --> 00:07:55.199
the former government documents
library here,

00:07:55.199 --> 00:07:59.754
we had and we still have many
environmental impact statements

00:07:59.754 --> 00:08:01.500
that you can request.
 

00:08:01.500 --> 00:08:03.826
Unfortunately,
you can't wander through the

00:08:03.826 --> 00:08:06.430
aisles anymore because it's been
closed down.

00:08:06.430 --> 00:08:09.668
But the university still
maintains these environmental

00:08:09.668 --> 00:08:13.028
impact statements that are
actually quite interesting to

00:08:13.028 --> 00:08:14.189
browse through.
 

00:08:14.189 --> 00:08:17.278
Well, I couldn't find this
impact statement.

00:08:17.278 --> 00:08:21.788
And then our social science
librarian put out a message on

00:08:21.788 --> 00:08:26.456
her email list and asked if
anybody in the nation might have

00:08:26.456 --> 00:08:27.959
a copy of this.
 

00:08:27.959 --> 00:08:30.413
And it turned out that one
person on this list of all

00:08:30.413 --> 00:08:33.200
university libraries and public
libraries responded yes,

00:08:33.200 --> 00:08:36.845
that he had collected all
military draft environmental

00:08:36.845 --> 00:08:39.428
impact statements,
including this one.

00:08:39.428 --> 00:08:40.600
So he Xeroxed it and sent it to
me.

00:08:40.600 --> 00:08:44.745
It turned out to be a goldmine
in that it demonstrated a

00:08:44.745 --> 00:08:48.666
variety of historical action on
the part of the Navy,

00:08:48.666 --> 00:08:51.379
including diagrams such as
this.

00:08:51.379 --> 00:08:53.490
You see the bombing range up
here on the upper left,

00:08:53.490 --> 00:08:57.710
but you also see in basically
the same scale,

00:08:57.710 --> 00:09:01.924
other maps that the Navy put
together showing where their

00:09:01.924 --> 00:09:05.961
targets were,
showing also color codings of

00:09:05.961 --> 00:09:08.393
these areas,
in this case,

00:09:08.393 --> 00:09:12.480
concentric circles,
that had the metric and the key

00:09:12.480 --> 00:09:17.225
number of bombs dropped or
pounds of bombs dropped per acre

00:09:17.225 --> 00:09:18.370
per year.
 

00:09:18.370 --> 00:09:21.756
So this proved to be really
important, to try to think

00:09:21.756 --> 00:09:24.759
through what was released,
when it was released,

00:09:24.759 --> 00:09:26.870
and where it might have gone.
 

00:09:26.870 --> 00:09:30.919
And one interesting thing is
that you see that this side of

00:09:30.919 --> 00:09:35.038
the bay over here looks like it
was continually targeted.

00:09:35.038 --> 00:09:37.913
In fact, tanks were located at
the top of hills,

00:09:37.913 --> 00:09:41.336
and they were clearly being
targeted, both by bombers but

00:09:41.336 --> 00:09:43.110
also by artillery shells.
 

00:09:43.110 --> 00:09:45.908
So gradually,
this area, this part of the

00:09:45.908 --> 00:09:48.220
landscape, was being flattened.
 

00:09:48.220 --> 00:09:52.230
And by flattening the beach
area at the end of that runway,

00:09:52.230 --> 00:09:55.323
they basically created a
trough, a trough by which that

00:09:55.323 --> 00:09:58.705
lagoon could drain all of the
material that it had collected

00:09:58.705 --> 00:09:59.678
into the bay.
 

00:09:59.678 --> 00:10:04.356
And also, I looked at this air
photograph maybe thirty or forty

00:10:04.356 --> 00:10:08.883
times and it hadn't dawned on me
that this little light patch

00:10:08.883 --> 00:10:13.408
right here seemed like it was
just an open area of sand.

00:10:13.408 --> 00:10:17.293
But you can track it on Google
Earth and find that it reaches

00:10:17.293 --> 00:10:20.658
down gradually and then fades
into sea grass beds.

00:10:20.658 --> 00:10:23.597
But clearly,
it's evidence that material has

00:10:23.597 --> 00:10:27.355
flowed out of that area and
killed the vegetation on the

00:10:27.355 --> 00:10:28.860
floor of this bay.
 

00:10:28.860 --> 00:10:31.548
The same thing happened on the
other site.

00:10:31.548 --> 00:10:35.495
And if you see these lines in
the diagram down here,

00:10:35.495 --> 00:10:40.291
these lines depict the bombing
route, so that planes would take

00:10:40.291 --> 00:10:42.690
off from aircraft carriers.
 

00:10:42.690 --> 00:10:46.269
They would fly up in this
direction on the east side.

00:10:46.269 --> 00:10:49.268
They'd circle around and come
back and fly back this way and

00:10:49.268 --> 00:10:50.590
bomb in both directions.
 

00:10:50.590 --> 00:10:55.019
So three or four fighter planes
would be doing this continually,

00:10:55.019 --> 00:10:58.399
year after year,
decade after decade,

00:10:58.399 --> 00:11:01.558
millions of pounds after
millions of pounds,

00:11:01.558 --> 00:11:06.460
so that they disclosed not just
pounds per acre per year,

00:11:06.460 --> 00:11:11.029
but total amount of munitions
so that the estimate of 100 to

00:11:11.029 --> 00:11:15.368
150 million pounds of ordinance
is basically derived from

00:11:15.368 --> 00:11:19.706
information that was provided in
the environmental impact

00:11:19.706 --> 00:11:23.424
statement that would not
otherwise have been made

00:11:23.424 --> 00:11:24.820
available.
 

00:11:24.820 --> 00:11:27.870
Since that time,
I've recognized also that the

00:11:27.870 --> 00:11:31.530
Navy has maintained a really
tough and tight accounting

00:11:31.530 --> 00:11:33.429
system of what they did.
 

00:11:33.429 --> 00:11:35.240
And how would I know that?
 

00:11:35.240 --> 00:11:38.538
Well, by talking to people that
were ordinance officers.

00:11:38.538 --> 00:11:41.246
And you recall those large
concrete bunkers,

00:11:41.246 --> 00:11:44.898
couple hundred concrete bunkers
up in the hills loaded with

00:11:44.898 --> 00:11:46.850
different kinds of weapons?
 

00:11:46.850 --> 00:11:49.863
Well, they were officers or
enlisted men that were

00:11:49.863 --> 00:11:53.370
responsible for the inventory in
each of the buildings.

00:11:53.370 --> 00:11:56.864
I mean, they want to know how
many nuclear weapons they've got

00:11:56.864 --> 00:11:59.269
and where they are at any point
in time.

00:11:59.269 --> 00:12:02.269
So they had kept their records
very neatly.

00:12:02.269 --> 00:12:06.485
Again, this information was not
included in the environmental

00:12:06.485 --> 00:12:09.576
impact statement,
but it provided a basis for

00:12:09.576 --> 00:12:10.629
litigation.
 

00:12:10.629 --> 00:12:16.594
So that this type of historical
documentation is often very

00:12:16.594 --> 00:12:18.960
difficult to come by.
 

00:12:18.960 --> 00:12:22.883
Another statute that has played
an important role here and in

00:12:22.883 --> 00:12:25.629
many hazardous sites around the
nation,

00:12:25.629 --> 00:12:28.450
is the Resource Conservation
and Recovery Act of 1976,

00:12:28.450 --> 00:12:32.188
which was designed to manage
both hazardous and nonhazardous

00:12:32.188 --> 00:12:33.777
waste,
and included the

00:12:33.777 --> 00:12:37.926
cradle-to-grave tracking system,
meaning that wastes or

00:12:37.926 --> 00:12:42.440
hazardous chemicals from their
time of creation,

00:12:42.440 --> 00:12:48.899
their movement via ship or by
rail or by tanker truck,

00:12:48.899 --> 00:12:53.168
and their ultimate disposal had
to be recorded.

00:12:53.168 --> 00:12:56.250
So it was a large-scale
national inventory system.

00:12:56.250 --> 00:12:59.631
And the key to this system,
just the Endangered Species Act

00:12:59.631 --> 00:13:03.014
that I was talking about the
other day or the Safe Drinking

00:13:03.014 --> 00:13:06.200
Water Act,
the core of the system and its

00:13:06.200 --> 00:13:09.096
Achilles' heel,
is really that the chemical has

00:13:09.096 --> 00:13:12.014
to be listed as a hazardous
substance to make its way onto

00:13:12.014 --> 00:13:12.629
the list.
 

00:13:12.629 --> 00:13:15.577
So you can imagine that adding
additional chemicals is

00:13:15.577 --> 00:13:18.692
something that the chemical
companies and people that use

00:13:18.692 --> 00:13:21.918
basic chemicals don't really
want to have happen because it

00:13:21.918 --> 00:13:24.811
increases their accounting
responsibilities and their

00:13:24.811 --> 00:13:27.759
reporting responsibilities to
the government.

00:13:27.759 --> 00:13:33.158
It included a hazardous waste
land disposal ban.

00:13:33.158 --> 00:13:36.020
And this is kind of
interesting, because there are

00:13:36.020 --> 00:13:39.116
about 300,000 community
landfills sprinkled around the

00:13:39.116 --> 00:13:39.759
nation.
 

00:13:39.759 --> 00:13:41.620
Every town has a landfill.
 

00:13:41.620 --> 00:13:45.171
They used to call them dumps,
now they call them sanitary

00:13:45.171 --> 00:13:49.039
landfills, which is an oxymoron
if anybody has any sense about

00:13:49.039 --> 00:13:50.690
what's happened there.
 

00:13:50.690 --> 00:13:54.995
But for much of history,
people have taken everything

00:13:54.995 --> 00:13:58.058
and just piled it up in a
landfill.

00:13:58.058 --> 00:14:00.895
And then by about 1950,
they started covering it over

00:14:00.895 --> 00:14:04.168
with soil, not thinking about
where the material might go.

00:14:04.168 --> 00:14:07.331
I remember when I was young
going to our local

00:14:07.331 --> 00:14:09.720
"dump,"
we called it,

00:14:09.720 --> 00:14:12.980
with my dad and watching trucks
pull up,

00:14:12.980 --> 00:14:15.778
oil trucks pull up and drain
their tanks into the piles of

00:14:15.778 --> 00:14:16.220
refuse.
 

00:14:16.220 --> 00:14:21.942
People that would pull up that
were mechanics that worked on

00:14:21.942 --> 00:14:26.874
people's heating systems,
and they would use solvents to

00:14:26.874 --> 00:14:30.269
take the grease off of
somebody's oil burner.

00:14:30.269 --> 00:14:34.039
And that grease and the solvent
would then just be thrown into

00:14:34.039 --> 00:14:34.720
the dump.
 

00:14:34.720 --> 00:14:38.115
So that if you dug down beneath
any of these sanitary landfills

00:14:38.115 --> 00:14:40.687
today,
you would find not just

00:14:40.687 --> 00:14:44.298
solvents and residues of oil and
fuel,

00:14:44.298 --> 00:14:46.288
but you'd find many other
chemicals,

00:14:46.288 --> 00:14:49.428
as plastics and other products
degrade,

00:14:49.428 --> 00:14:52.110
just leaching into the soil and
to underlying water.

00:14:52.110 --> 00:14:55.220
So that preventing land
disposal was a very significant

00:14:55.220 --> 00:14:56.658
provision back in 1984.
 

00:14:56.658 --> 00:15:00.610
Also, the underground storage
tank program is located in this

00:15:00.610 --> 00:15:01.269
statute.
 

00:15:01.269 --> 00:15:05.541
And it requires an inventory
and monitoring of underground

00:15:05.541 --> 00:15:06.740
storage tanks.
 

00:15:06.740 --> 00:15:10.815
And you can imagine that
underground storage tanks that

00:15:10.815 --> 00:15:15.192
contain gasoline or other fuels
or oils sitting beneath the

00:15:15.192 --> 00:15:19.342
surface in a steel tank designed
to last forty years has

00:15:19.342 --> 00:15:22.509
contaminated many,
many sites.

00:15:22.509 --> 00:15:25.263
Those gas stations that you see
with the yellow ribbons around

00:15:25.263 --> 00:15:25.580
them?
 

00:15:25.580 --> 00:15:27.490
They basically are regulated
under this statute.

00:15:27.490 --> 00:15:30.927
And they are a product of some
engineer who had the bright

00:15:30.927 --> 00:15:33.251
idea,
probably back around 1920 or

00:15:33.251 --> 00:15:37.003
1930, that a forty-year life
cycle for a storage tank made

00:15:37.003 --> 00:15:40.029
out of steel was going to be an
okay thing.

00:15:40.029 --> 00:15:43.376
So what's the life cycle of a
storage barrel,

00:15:43.376 --> 00:15:46.418
a fifty-five gallon drum,
for example?

00:15:46.418 --> 00:15:51.488
So this design error has
polluted ground water and soil

00:15:51.488 --> 00:15:54.210
literally around the world.
 

00:15:54.210 --> 00:15:57.543
And used oils as well,
what happens to that oil that

00:15:57.543 --> 00:16:01.269
your mechanic drains out of your
car when you get your oil

00:16:01.269 --> 00:16:03.230
changed every 3,000 miles?
 

00:16:03.230 --> 00:16:06.730
Well, it used to be just taken
to the town landfill.

00:16:06.730 --> 00:16:10.428
So this statute prevented that
from happening.

00:16:10.428 --> 00:16:13.980
So Vieques was like any other
community, it had many of these

00:16:13.980 --> 00:16:15.460
landfills, so to speak.
 

00:16:15.460 --> 00:16:19.360
And it was a repository for a
variety of hazardous chemicals.

00:16:19.360 --> 00:16:24.168
So key RCRA controversies that
have emerged include the listing

00:16:24.168 --> 00:16:26.960
issue, what's hazardous,
mixtures.

00:16:26.960 --> 00:16:29.404
If a waste is mixed with
nonhazardous waste,

00:16:29.404 --> 00:16:30.769
is it still hazardous?
 

00:16:30.769 --> 00:16:34.557
This has been a debate that has
been intensely litigated with

00:16:34.557 --> 00:16:37.399
the idea that dilution is not
the solution.

00:16:37.399 --> 00:16:41.285
The idea that motor oils,
some of them are exempted,

00:16:41.285 --> 00:16:43.418
even though they're toxic.
 

00:16:43.418 --> 00:16:45.509
That's been the subject of much
litigation.

00:16:45.509 --> 00:16:47.120
Household wastes also.
 

00:16:47.120 --> 00:16:52.470
Can they be mixed up with more
hazardous waste?

00:16:52.470 --> 00:16:55.110
Mining and oil production
wastes have been excluded.

00:16:55.110 --> 00:16:58.986
And one interesting provision
in this case is that corporate

00:16:58.986 --> 00:17:02.470
officials can be found guilty of
criminal behavior.

00:17:02.470 --> 00:17:07.270
So the standard of evidence for
a criminal case is different

00:17:07.270 --> 00:17:10.180
than a civil case,
a civil action,

00:17:10.180 --> 00:17:14.980
whereby a civil action would be
decided by a preponderance of

00:17:14.980 --> 00:17:18.237
the evidence,
which means that it's more

00:17:18.237 --> 00:17:21.230
likely than not that damage was
induced.

00:17:21.230 --> 00:17:26.788
But a criminal case demands a
higher burden of proof,

00:17:26.788 --> 00:17:30.969
meaning basically that it has
to be demonstrated that a causal

00:17:30.969 --> 00:17:33.710
link exists beyond a reasonable
doubt.

00:17:33.710 --> 00:17:36.249
And RCRA also,
as I mentioned earlier,

00:17:36.249 --> 00:17:38.720
contains a citizen suit
provision.

00:17:38.720 --> 00:17:43.069
So by 1986, about 27,000
contaminated sites had been

00:17:43.069 --> 00:17:44.180
identified.
 

00:17:44.180 --> 00:17:48.549
And as I mentioned the other
day, now there are more than

00:17:48.549 --> 00:17:53.154
300,000 contaminated sites in
the private sector and perhaps

00:17:53.154 --> 00:17:56.509
50,000 to 100,000 in the public
sector.

00:17:56.509 --> 00:18:00.791
Another statute that is at play
here is the Emergency Planning

00:18:00.791 --> 00:18:04.583
and Community Right to Know Act
that's contained in the

00:18:04.583 --> 00:18:06.900
Superfund amendments of 1986.
 

00:18:06.900 --> 00:18:10.519
And this basically gave every
community the right to know

00:18:10.519 --> 00:18:13.298
about chemicals that are made
by, stored in,

00:18:13.298 --> 00:18:15.690
or emitted from local
businesses.

00:18:15.690 --> 00:18:20.740
This evolved after many first
responders experienced toxic

00:18:20.740 --> 00:18:26.412
reactions to chemicals that were
stored in buildings that were on

00:18:26.412 --> 00:18:27.210
fire.
 

00:18:27.210 --> 00:18:32.422
So they went in to put the fire
out and received intensive

00:18:32.422 --> 00:18:33.519
exposures.
 

00:18:33.519 --> 00:18:35.338
And it created something called
the Toxic Release Inventory.

00:18:35.338 --> 00:18:41.963
The Toxic Release Inventory is
a list of who releases what,

00:18:41.963 --> 00:18:44.019
where, and when.
 

00:18:44.019 --> 00:18:47.030
And it has to be provided on an
annual basis to the

00:18:47.030 --> 00:18:51.821
Environmental Protection Agency,
but only if the chemical is put

00:18:51.821 --> 00:18:56.839
on the list and only if it's
produced or present at a level

00:18:56.839 --> 00:19:01.078
that exceeds a certain volume or
weight limit.

00:19:01.078 --> 00:19:05.269
So the SARA amendments
authorized additional funds for

00:19:05.269 --> 00:19:10.805
National Priority List sites,
mandated public involvement,

00:19:10.805 --> 00:19:17.138
provided permanent remedies to
restore sites or to basically

00:19:17.138 --> 00:19:19.930
pay for proven damages.
 

00:19:19.930 --> 00:19:23.342
It also requires something
known as best available

00:19:23.342 --> 00:19:25.848
technologies to clean up the
site.

00:19:25.848 --> 00:19:29.932
So a huge question in all these
cases is once a site is

00:19:29.932 --> 00:19:33.108
contaminated,
how should it be restored?

00:19:33.108 --> 00:19:34.950
What's the standard for
restoration?

00:19:34.950 --> 00:19:36.269
Is it pre-human?
 

00:19:36.269 --> 00:19:39.430
Is it a certain risk-based
standard so that it's okay to

00:19:39.430 --> 00:19:42.762
have a little bit of lead or a
little bit of benzene in the

00:19:42.762 --> 00:19:45.118
soil or the groundwater or the
trees?

00:19:45.118 --> 00:19:47.740
So these are very difficult
questions.

00:19:47.740 --> 00:19:52.213
No site is cleaned up back to
its pre-polluted condition

00:19:52.213 --> 00:19:56.607
completely, so residues are
always detectible in all of

00:19:56.607 --> 00:19:57.910
these cases.
 

00:19:57.910 --> 00:20:01.450
State standards apply if they
are more stringent.

00:20:01.450 --> 00:20:05.416
And this is an interesting
provision, because it's one of

00:20:05.416 --> 00:20:09.880
the few laws that allows states
to preempt federal standards.

00:20:09.880 --> 00:20:14.470
So the Clean Air Act basically
preempts Connecticut,

00:20:14.470 --> 00:20:17.680
for example,
from having tougher standards

00:20:17.680 --> 00:20:22.298
than the federal government to
emit chemicals to the air.

00:20:22.298 --> 00:20:27.298
But unless, and we'll talk
about this in a week or so,

00:20:27.298 --> 00:20:31.250
unless Connecticut is out of
compliance with the Clean Air

00:20:31.250 --> 00:20:34.960
Act standards,
then we have to meet California

00:20:34.960 --> 00:20:37.098
standards,
which are the toughest in the

00:20:37.098 --> 00:20:37.420
nation.
 

00:20:37.420 --> 00:20:40.241
So the idea of preemption,
preventing a lower level of

00:20:40.241 --> 00:20:43.332
government from passing a law
that is more stringent at the

00:20:43.332 --> 00:20:46.892
federal level of government,
is very desirable from the

00:20:46.892 --> 00:20:49.319
perspective of the private
sector.

00:20:49.319 --> 00:20:51.130
Now, why would that be?
 

00:20:51.130 --> 00:20:55.990
Basically, you'd want kind of a
common ground,

00:20:55.990 --> 00:20:59.474
you want to deal with only one
set of regulations rather than

00:20:59.474 --> 00:21:03.134
worrying about moving your goods
or your material or whatever it

00:21:03.134 --> 00:21:04.321
is,
your service,

00:21:04.321 --> 00:21:07.213
across state boundaries and
having to negotiate fifty

00:21:07.213 --> 00:21:09.048
different sets of regulations.
 

00:21:09.048 --> 00:21:13.255
So this is a really important
statutory provision that

00:21:13.255 --> 00:21:16.348
includes the citizen suit
provisions.

00:21:16.348 --> 00:21:19.838
Litigation basically stalled
out RCRA.

00:21:19.838 --> 00:21:22.969
And it stalled out Superfund
cleanups during much of the

00:21:22.969 --> 00:21:26.155
1980s and 1990s predominately
because of the citizen suit

00:21:26.155 --> 00:21:28.538
provision,
it's an interesting thing.

00:21:28.538 --> 00:21:32.200
So that potentially responsible
parties would then sue the

00:21:32.200 --> 00:21:34.819
government,
claiming that they really were

00:21:34.819 --> 00:21:38.031
not the primary responsible
party or that they should pay

00:21:38.031 --> 00:21:41.588
only for the proportion of the
material that was hazardous that

00:21:41.588 --> 00:21:43.308
was detected on the site.
 

00:21:43.308 --> 00:21:47.859
So the Superfund amendments of
1986 prevented certain forms of

00:21:47.859 --> 00:21:51.962
litigation by potentially
responsible parties or parties

00:21:51.962 --> 00:21:55.319
that EPA had declared to be
responsible,

00:21:55.319 --> 00:21:57.750
and things sped up.
 

00:21:57.750 --> 00:22:02.116
The Vieques story was also
affected by these amendments in

00:22:02.116 --> 00:22:05.755
one way,
in that it created the Agency

00:22:05.755 --> 00:22:09.900
for Toxic Substance and Disease
Registry,

00:22:09.900 --> 00:22:11.808
that's quite a mouthful for a
federal agency.

00:22:11.808 --> 00:22:15.036
It sits inside the Centers for
Disease Control,

00:22:15.036 --> 00:22:17.000
based in Atlanta,
Georgia.

00:22:17.000 --> 00:22:20.962
And this group has the
responsibility to respond to any

00:22:20.962 --> 00:22:25.294
community that petitions the
federal government arguing that

00:22:25.294 --> 00:22:28.548
they have been damaged,
either their property or their

00:22:28.548 --> 00:22:32.862
health has been damaged,
by federal actions that are now

00:22:32.862 --> 00:22:36.240
declared to be Superfund sites.
 

00:22:36.240 --> 00:22:40.061
So it allows the citizens of
the nation to basically get

00:22:40.061 --> 00:22:43.953
expert scientific advice to
figure out what chemicals are

00:22:43.953 --> 00:22:48.124
released and how people might be
exposed and what the hazards

00:22:48.124 --> 00:22:48.818
are.
 

00:22:48.818 --> 00:22:53.327
And this agency has played a
really unusual role in that they

00:22:53.327 --> 00:22:56.037
very,
very rarely in their history,

00:22:56.037 --> 00:23:00.049
now they're twenty-three,
twenty-four years old,

00:23:00.049 --> 00:23:04.894
they very rarely have found
that there was conclusive

00:23:04.894 --> 00:23:08.528
evidence that the wastes on a
site,

00:23:08.528 --> 00:23:13.835
that the hazardous materials
released produced adverse health

00:23:13.835 --> 00:23:14.720
effects.
 

00:23:14.720 --> 00:23:18.814
So in 2003, they went down to
Vieques because one of the

00:23:18.814 --> 00:23:22.759
islanders petitioned the agency
with this question.

00:23:22.759 --> 00:23:26.003
And they went about their
business looking for whether or

00:23:26.003 --> 00:23:29.480
not the contaminants in drinking
water might be a problem.

00:23:29.480 --> 00:23:31.410
And they concluded no,
the drinking water is okay.

00:23:31.410 --> 00:23:35.090
The water comes from a national
forest which is on the mainland

00:23:35.090 --> 00:23:37.980
of Puerto Rico,
and it's actually piped six

00:23:37.980 --> 00:23:41.420
miles underneath the bay to the
island of Vieques.

00:23:41.420 --> 00:23:44.371
They also concluded that now
that the Navy had left the

00:23:44.371 --> 00:23:47.759
island that the air quality was
sufficient so that that did not

00:23:47.759 --> 00:23:50.328
pose a significant threat to the
community.

00:23:50.328 --> 00:23:53.681
They also concluded that the
food that was grown on the

00:23:53.681 --> 00:23:57.218
island and the fish that were
caught in the coastal waters

00:23:57.218 --> 00:24:01.500
were not contaminated at a level
that posed a significant threat.

00:24:01.500 --> 00:24:06.727
So they virtually washed their
hands of this being a

00:24:06.727 --> 00:24:10.519
significant threat to human
health.

00:24:10.519 --> 00:24:13.994
And they dismissed all of the
claims on the part of the

00:24:13.994 --> 00:24:17.727
Vieques residents who believed
that the Navy's behavior and

00:24:17.727 --> 00:24:21.460
their contamination caused a
whole array of different kinds

00:24:21.460 --> 00:24:23.519
of adverse health effects.
 

00:24:23.519 --> 00:24:31.994
A lawsuit was filed on behalf
of 7,100 residents on the island

00:24:31.994 --> 00:24:40.471
in 2007 that claimed that the
Navy was responsible for loss of

00:24:40.471 --> 00:24:42.000
health.
 

00:24:42.000 --> 00:24:44.194
And the government's response
has been really quite

00:24:44.194 --> 00:24:44.808
interesting.
 

00:24:44.808 --> 00:24:49.660
In one respect,
they responded that well,

00:24:49.660 --> 00:24:52.509
they are protected by sovereign
immunity,

00:24:52.509 --> 00:24:57.894
which basically is an argument
that the king is immune from any

00:24:57.894 --> 00:25:02.795
litigation,
that the king should not be

00:25:02.795 --> 00:25:07.710
held accountable for past
behavior.

00:25:07.710 --> 00:25:10.817
They also argued that bringing
a class action lawsuit

00:25:10.817 --> 00:25:14.462
representing a large group of
people like this but focusing in

00:25:14.462 --> 00:25:18.048
on a representative sample of
that group so that you wouldn't

00:25:18.048 --> 00:25:21.394
have to litigate and develop
evidence for each individual

00:25:21.394 --> 00:25:22.828
among the 7,100.
 

00:25:22.828 --> 00:25:28.240
The Justice Department believed
that this should be handled case

00:25:28.240 --> 00:25:29.098
by case.
 

00:25:29.098 --> 00:25:32.313
Now, here's a community that is
well, well below the national

00:25:32.313 --> 00:25:33.170
poverty level.
 

00:25:33.170 --> 00:25:36.210
They had no resources to mount
a case like this.

00:25:36.210 --> 00:25:40.048
So that several law firms have
picked this up.

00:25:40.048 --> 00:25:43.680
And one in particular has been
pursuing Sanchez versus the

00:25:43.680 --> 00:25:44.700
United States.
 

00:25:44.700 --> 00:25:48.269
And by some mysterious
coincidence,

00:25:48.269 --> 00:25:53.234
there was a convergence of this
lecture and the lecture on

00:25:53.234 --> 00:25:58.635
Tuesday and a CNN documentary on
Vieques that was released this

00:25:58.635 --> 00:25:59.420
week.
 

