00:31:53.680 --> 00:31:54.900
Video voiceover:
: This is American territory.

00:31:54.900 --> 00:31:57.410
The people that live here are
Americans.

00:31:57.410 --> 00:32:02.259
And how do you do something in
your own back yard,

00:32:02.259 --> 00:32:07.211
and you hurt someone,
you have to take care of that

00:32:07.211 --> 00:32:08.298
person.
 

00:32:08.298 --> 00:32:12.470
And the government's just not
doing anything about it.

00:32:12.470 --> 00:32:23.269
&gt;
 

00:32:23.269 --> 00:32:25.440
&gt;
 

00:32:25.440 --> 00:32:27.250
Prof: All right,
now as you reflect on that,

00:32:27.250 --> 00:32:29.390
you should be asking yourself a
whole bunch of questions.

00:32:29.390 --> 00:32:34.935
One of them would be,
here's a gentleman who is now

00:32:34.935 --> 00:32:36.490
mid-fifties.
 

00:32:36.490 --> 00:32:38.670
He obviously has many different
medical problems.

00:32:38.670 --> 00:32:43.830
But he faces a serious burden
of proof of exposure to

00:32:43.830 --> 00:32:48.098
chemicals that were released by
the Navy.

00:32:48.098 --> 00:32:50.480
So how would you think that
through?

00:32:50.480 --> 00:32:53.480
How would you make that
connection?

00:32:53.480 --> 00:32:56.614
One question you might ask is,
were the chemicals that they

00:32:56.614 --> 00:32:59.531
described in the lawsuit that
were released by the Navy

00:32:59.531 --> 00:33:00.828
present in his body?
 

00:33:00.828 --> 00:33:02.998
Well, you know,
the historical reconstruction

00:33:02.998 --> 00:33:05.710
problem that I mentioned on
Tuesday is extraordinary.

00:33:05.710 --> 00:33:09.711
It's incredibly complex
scientifically and would be very

00:33:09.711 --> 00:33:13.785
expensive to document how long
do these chemicals last in

00:33:13.785 --> 00:33:15.240
somebody's body?
 

00:33:15.240 --> 00:33:18.150
What are plausible alternative
sources of exposure?

00:33:18.150 --> 00:33:23.148
You know, the Navy argued that
heavy metals used in the weapons

00:33:23.148 --> 00:33:27.987
were also minerals that had been
driven by winds from Saharan

00:33:27.987 --> 00:33:32.180
dust storms across the Pacific
and rained down,

00:33:32.180 --> 00:33:33.880
and perhaps that's a route of
exposure.

00:33:33.880 --> 00:33:36.460
So the Navy's been very good,
along with the Justice

00:33:36.460 --> 00:33:39.090
Department, in developing these
plausible alternative

00:33:39.090 --> 00:33:39.848
hypotheses.
 

00:33:39.848 --> 00:33:43.390
Another has been the
ritualistic use of mercury.

00:33:43.390 --> 00:33:47.423
Did the mercury come from Navy
switches in the bombs that

00:33:47.423 --> 00:33:50.885
leaked out on that site,
made its way into the Marine

00:33:50.885 --> 00:33:52.837
food chain,
built up, and then made its way

00:33:52.837 --> 00:33:54.690
to the dinner table and into
people's bodies?

00:33:54.690 --> 00:33:58.558
Or did it come from an electric
plant that was located on the

00:33:58.558 --> 00:33:59.140
island?
 

00:33:59.140 --> 00:34:03.019
Or could it have come from any
fish in the area?

00:34:03.019 --> 00:34:07.230
When the Agency for Toxic
Substances and Disease Registry

00:34:07.230 --> 00:34:11.646
did their fish sample,
they wandered around the island

00:34:11.646 --> 00:34:15.329
sampling fish from many
different locations.

00:34:15.329 --> 00:34:19.067
But as I mentioned,
often the sample sizes were

00:34:19.067 --> 00:34:22.480
incredibly small,
less than ten in size.

00:34:22.480 --> 00:34:27.023
So what you'd want to do is,
you'd want to know that these

00:34:27.023 --> 00:34:31.409
chemicals had moved in a
gradient from their location of

00:34:31.409 --> 00:34:34.360
release further and further
away.

00:34:34.360 --> 00:34:37.065
And you hoped to find a
declining gradient in the

00:34:37.065 --> 00:34:40.110
concentration as you moved
further and further away.

00:34:40.110 --> 00:34:42.489
But they didn't conduct this
kind of work.

00:34:42.489 --> 00:34:44.793
James Porter,
who is the professor at the

00:34:44.793 --> 00:34:48.309
University of Georgia that I
mentioned, has done that work.

00:34:48.309 --> 00:34:51.340
As you move further and further
away from the bombed area,

00:34:51.340 --> 00:34:52.829
you do see these declines.
 

00:34:52.829 --> 00:34:55.204
So key questions that are
raised by this video,

00:34:55.204 --> 00:34:58.150
what was the prior knowledge of
the Defense Department?

00:34:58.150 --> 00:35:01.184
I know that the Defense
Department had very accurate

00:35:01.184 --> 00:35:04.637
records of the ordinance that
was released and where it was

00:35:04.637 --> 00:35:06.900
released and when it was
released.

00:35:06.900 --> 00:35:09.619
Another key question is,
should this move forward as a

00:35:09.619 --> 00:35:10.800
class action lawsuit?
 

00:35:10.800 --> 00:35:16.724
If the courts find that it
cannot, that it has to be judged

00:35:16.724 --> 00:35:19.300
individually,
person by person,

00:35:19.300 --> 00:35:22.681
there's no hope that this would
be concluded in the next fifty

00:35:22.681 --> 00:35:23.179
years.
 

00:35:23.179 --> 00:35:26.380
The idea of sovereign
immunity--should the United

00:35:26.380 --> 00:35:27.980
States be responsible?
 

00:35:27.980 --> 00:35:31.519
And this is spoken to quite
clearly in a variety of

00:35:31.519 --> 00:35:35.626
environmental statutes that I
described to you just fifteen

00:35:35.626 --> 00:35:36.760
minutes ago.
 

00:35:36.760 --> 00:35:40.492
But the central,
core question here is one of

00:35:40.492 --> 00:35:41.510
causation.
 

00:35:41.510 --> 00:35:44.739
Did these chemicals cause those
illnesses?

00:35:44.739 --> 00:35:48.119
What's the matchup between the
chemicals released,

00:35:48.119 --> 00:35:49.739
the chemicals found in people's
bodies,

00:35:49.739 --> 00:35:52.347
and what we know medically
about the effects of those

00:35:52.347 --> 00:35:52.949
chemicals?
 

00:35:52.949 --> 00:35:54.360
This is very difficult science.
 

00:35:54.360 --> 00:35:58.139
To be held to a standard of
scientific proof,

00:35:58.139 --> 00:36:01.096
say ninety-nine percent
confidence that there is this

00:36:01.096 --> 00:36:04.280
established cause and effect
relationship would virtually

00:36:04.280 --> 00:36:07.750
make it impossible for this
community to recover damages.

00:36:07.750 --> 00:36:13.210
Beyond a reasonable doubt,
it's a different matter.

00:36:13.210 --> 00:36:17.851
So what you see here is you see
the media getting behind this

00:36:17.851 --> 00:36:19.936
case,
being sympathetic,

00:36:19.936 --> 00:36:24.090
having a very clear story about
chemical release,

00:36:24.090 --> 00:36:26.260
not really knowing where it
went.

00:36:26.260 --> 00:36:31.148
Not really fully understanding
what people's exposures were,

00:36:31.148 --> 00:36:35.373
how they might have been
exposed via air or water or

00:36:35.373 --> 00:36:36.119
food.
 

00:36:36.119 --> 00:36:40.789
But you also have a community
that has lived in an environment

00:36:40.789 --> 00:36:44.159
that socially has been seriously
affected.

00:36:44.159 --> 00:36:47.737
There is no debate about the
fact that the presence of the

00:36:47.737 --> 00:36:51.628
military put the economy of that
island in the freezer for much

00:36:51.628 --> 00:36:53.449
of the twentieth century.
 

00:36:53.449 --> 00:36:57.489
And the impact of that in
diminishing their income,

00:36:57.489 --> 00:37:01.722
diminishing their access to
basic public services such as

00:37:01.722 --> 00:37:05.710
education and healthcare,
such as early detection,

00:37:05.710 --> 00:37:10.391
having to travel off the island
when you don't own a car to a

00:37:10.391 --> 00:37:14.056
hospital on the mainland of
Puerto Rico is a big

00:37:14.056 --> 00:37:17.489
disincentive to get early
medical care.

00:37:17.489 --> 00:37:21.059
So late medical care translates
into a higher incidence of

00:37:21.059 --> 00:37:24.942
disease and detection when the
illness has progressed to become

00:37:24.942 --> 00:37:28.266
more serious,
becomes more difficult to

00:37:28.266 --> 00:37:28.969
manage.
 

00:37:28.969 --> 00:37:31.974
Also, everyone is thinking
about "Okay,

00:37:31.974 --> 00:37:34.559
what is the cost going to
be?"

00:37:34.559 --> 00:37:37.039
What's a likely cost for this
one site?

00:37:37.039 --> 00:37:39.889
And remember the figure that I
showed you the other day,

00:37:39.889 --> 00:37:45.646
that Congress allocates roughly
two to $2.5 billion dollars per

00:37:45.646 --> 00:37:49.360
year for the entire Superfund
program.

00:37:49.360 --> 00:37:52.867
Whereas plausibly,
it could take up to a billion

00:37:52.867 --> 00:37:57.047
dollars to clean this area and
also to provide sufficient

00:37:57.047 --> 00:37:59.659
medical care for the community.
 

00:37:59.659 --> 00:38:04.264
And also remember the fact that
many of these families had

00:38:04.264 --> 00:38:08.949
earlier generations that were
plucked up off their property

00:38:08.949 --> 00:38:10.079
and moved.
 

00:38:10.079 --> 00:38:13.143
How would you think about
compensating them for their loss

00:38:13.143 --> 00:38:14.219
of property value?
 

00:38:14.219 --> 00:38:18.119
Given $25 in 1945 for a tract
of land,

00:38:18.119 --> 00:38:23.239
or for the costs incurred by
having your house bulldozed and

00:38:23.239 --> 00:38:28.360
having the family move to a
different part of the island.

00:38:28.360 --> 00:38:31.815
So it also raises a very
interesting counterpoint to the

00:38:31.815 --> 00:38:35.018
Marshall Islands case that we
saw the other week.

00:38:35.018 --> 00:38:38.788
And that is that when the
United States decided to take

00:38:38.788 --> 00:38:42.556
over the Marshall Islands,
they did so thinking that no

00:38:42.556 --> 00:38:45.210
one could survive an attack
there.

00:38:45.210 --> 00:38:47.530
They had to move everybody out
of the islands that they bombed.

00:38:47.530 --> 00:38:50.630
In this case,
they believed that they could

00:38:50.630 --> 00:38:55.132
conduct their weapons testing in
a way that would not harm the

00:38:55.132 --> 00:38:56.239
population.
 

00:38:56.239 --> 00:38:59.027
If they concentrated them in
the center of the island and

00:38:59.027 --> 00:39:01.766
they bombed the end of the
island, they weren't thinking

00:39:01.766 --> 00:39:03.360
ecologically about pathways.
 

00:39:03.360 --> 00:39:04.809
They weren't thinking about
diet.

00:39:04.809 --> 00:39:07.516
They weren't thinking about
airborne dust and prevailing

00:39:07.516 --> 00:39:07.909
winds.
 

00:39:07.909 --> 00:39:12.440
So that the idea that they
should move the entire

00:39:12.440 --> 00:39:16.690
population off the island was
reconsidered.

00:39:16.690 --> 00:39:20.947
There are now available
documents demonstrating that

00:39:20.947 --> 00:39:25.539
John Kennedy thought very,
very carefully about this.

00:39:25.539 --> 00:39:28.268
And Kennedy,
you remember was president

00:39:28.268 --> 00:39:30.280
during the Cuban invasion.
 

00:39:30.280 --> 00:39:34.592
And Vieques was a very
important base for staging for

00:39:34.592 --> 00:39:37.079
the invasion of Bay of Pigs.
 

00:39:37.079 --> 00:39:40.172
And what Kennedy was thinking
about was okay,

00:39:40.172 --> 00:39:44.458
why don't we completely remove
the islanders and resettle them

00:39:44.458 --> 00:39:46.989
in other parts of the Caribbean?
 

00:39:46.989 --> 00:39:49.210
He decided against that move.
 

00:39:49.210 --> 00:39:52.822
But that decision perhaps has
come back to haunt the

00:39:52.822 --> 00:39:56.650
government, and certainly is
haunting the islanders.

00:39:56.650 --> 00:40:02.713
However, this whole mess is a
product of misunderstanding

00:40:02.713 --> 00:40:09.405
basic ecological principles,
as well as I think a disregard

00:40:09.405 --> 00:40:14.190
for the long-term health of the
community.

00:40:14.190 --> 00:40:17.550
There are a couple of other
statutes here that are at play.

00:40:17.550 --> 00:40:23.632
And I wanted to bring your
attention to the Wilderness Act

00:40:23.632 --> 00:40:24.699
of 1964.
 

00:40:24.699 --> 00:40:30.009
And this statute is quite
interesting in that it defines

00:40:30.009 --> 00:40:33.297
wilderness as,
"An area in contrast with

00:40:33.297 --> 00:40:36.099
those areas where man and his
own works dominate the

00:40:36.099 --> 00:40:38.510
landscape,
is hereby recognized as an area

00:40:38.510 --> 00:40:40.840
where the Earth and its
community of life are

00:40:40.840 --> 00:40:43.681
untrammeled by man,
where man himself is a visitor

00:40:43.681 --> 00:40:45.139
who does not remain."
 

00:40:45.139 --> 00:40:49.400
And it goes on to define
characteristics of an area that

00:40:49.400 --> 00:40:53.427
would have to be met before it
could be designated as

00:40:53.427 --> 00:40:54.590
wilderness.
 

00:40:54.590 --> 00:40:59.239
But at the same time that the
government left Vieques and

00:40:59.239 --> 00:41:04.137
transferred jurisdiction to the
Fish and Wildlife Service to

00:41:04.137 --> 00:41:05.550
create a U.S.
 

00:41:05.550 --> 00:41:09.054
Fish and Wildlife Refuge on the
island, Congress decided that it

00:41:09.054 --> 00:41:12.280
was also going to declare the
area a federal wilderness.

00:41:12.280 --> 00:41:15.644
So it is distinctive in the
United States right now because

00:41:15.644 --> 00:41:19.753
it is the only Superfund site,
reserved for the most hazardous

00:41:19.753 --> 00:41:22.900
sites in the nation,
that is also declared to be a

00:41:22.900 --> 00:41:26.733
wilderness area,
a paradox that maybe you could

00:41:26.733 --> 00:41:32.190
explain to me,
especially looking at the site.

00:41:32.190 --> 00:41:36.985
The government clearly thought
that it would give them greater

00:41:36.985 --> 00:41:41.105
power to exclude people,
which they think they're doing

00:41:41.105 --> 00:41:43.500
well by posting signs on the
beach.

00:41:43.500 --> 00:41:47.487
This is a sign that is right on
the edge of the water that is

00:41:47.487 --> 00:41:51.474
within perhaps a hundred yards
of tanks sitting on a hillside

00:41:51.474 --> 00:41:54.996
that became the target for
planes as well as artillery

00:41:54.996 --> 00:41:55.860
shells.
 

00:41:55.860 --> 00:42:00.974
So the idea that you could post
a sign and it would keep people

00:42:00.974 --> 00:42:01.469
out.
 

00:42:01.469 --> 00:42:07.119
I took a research crew out
there several years ago.

00:42:07.119 --> 00:42:10.699
And one afternoon,
there were six or eight large

00:42:10.699 --> 00:42:14.813
pleasure boats all lined up
about fifty yards from this

00:42:14.813 --> 00:42:15.500
sign.
 

00:42:15.500 --> 00:42:19.639
Kids were out swimming in the
water, playing on the beach.

00:42:19.639 --> 00:42:23.255
So the idea that you could
control people via signs,

00:42:23.255 --> 00:42:26.659
with no other presence,
it defies explanation.

00:42:26.659 --> 00:42:32.114
Another statute that's at play
here is the Endangered Species

00:42:32.114 --> 00:42:32.659
Act.
 

00:42:32.659 --> 00:42:35.639
And the purposes of this
statute, passed in 1973,

00:42:35.639 --> 00:42:38.996
are to provide a means whereby
the ecosystems upon which

00:42:38.996 --> 00:42:42.170
endangered species and
threatened species depend,

00:42:42.170 --> 00:42:45.780
may be conserved to provide a
program for their conservation.

00:42:45.780 --> 00:42:52.114
So certain types of acts,
including damaging the habitat

00:42:52.114 --> 00:42:57.443
of an endangered species,
or taking an endangered species

00:42:57.443 --> 00:43:00.498
and either shooting it,
by killing an endangered

00:43:00.498 --> 00:43:03.380
species, you are taking it,
under this statute.

00:43:03.380 --> 00:43:07.876
So this law,
again, passed back in 1973,

00:43:07.876 --> 00:43:09.489
and the U.S.
 

00:43:09.489 --> 00:43:13.831
left the island in 2003,
there were three decades during

00:43:13.831 --> 00:43:17.860
which species declared to be
rare or endangered,

00:43:17.860 --> 00:43:21.400
particularly the turtles that
lived on the island,

00:43:21.400 --> 00:43:25.489
were clearly being affected by
military behavior and maneuvers.

00:43:25.489 --> 00:43:28.521
So here's a list of the
species, if any of you happen to

00:43:28.521 --> 00:43:30.119
be particularly interested.
 

00:43:30.119 --> 00:43:34.626
So I'm going to have to scoot
ahead here, so we can keep

00:43:34.626 --> 00:43:35.610
moving on.
 

00:43:35.610 --> 00:43:40.786
But I wanted you to recognize
that this history of military

00:43:40.786 --> 00:43:43.402
action,
of training,

00:43:43.402 --> 00:43:49.143
basically testing weapons,
of staging maneuvers that

00:43:49.143 --> 00:43:53.324
preceded major military actions,
it's created a legacy of

00:43:53.324 --> 00:43:56.920
severely contaminated sites
around the nation.

00:43:56.920 --> 00:43:59.884
Here's Johnston Atoll,
which is now the Pacific

00:43:59.884 --> 00:44:02.139
Islands National Wildlife
Refuge.

00:44:02.139 --> 00:44:05.760
So you see, there actually is a
pattern of taking a former

00:44:05.760 --> 00:44:08.110
highly contaminated military
base,

00:44:08.110 --> 00:44:12.280
transferring its jurisdiction
into a Fish and Wildlife refuge.

00:44:12.280 --> 00:44:15.355
This may look like the
moonscape, but this is the

00:44:15.355 --> 00:44:19.563
atomic testing site in Nevada,
where you can see the craters

00:44:19.563 --> 00:44:23.969
that are the result of hundreds
of other above ground tests.

00:44:23.969 --> 00:44:28.143
Here's another highly
contaminated site in Hanford,

00:44:28.143 --> 00:44:29.230
Washington.
 

00:44:29.230 --> 00:44:32.148
The Hanford Works,
the site of the Green Run,

00:44:32.148 --> 00:44:35.929
that you could read about in
Green Intelligence.

00:44:35.929 --> 00:44:39.746
The underground storage tanks,
the same problem that I

00:44:39.746 --> 00:44:42.340
mentioned earlier in the
lecture,

00:44:42.340 --> 00:44:47.242
leaking radioactive waste that
is highly concentrated into the

00:44:47.242 --> 00:44:48.610
Columbia River.
 

00:44:48.610 --> 00:44:54.777
The Columbia River is a habitat
for Pacific salmon and many

00:44:54.777 --> 00:44:57.329
other species of fish.
 

00:44:57.329 --> 00:45:00.760
And it's a very highly prized
region.

00:45:00.760 --> 00:45:03.788
The military reservation on
Cape Cod provides one more

00:45:03.788 --> 00:45:04.360
example.
 

00:45:04.360 --> 00:45:09.489
This reservation has a history
that spanned just about the same

00:45:09.489 --> 00:45:14.041
amount of time as Vieques,
from about 1940 to just about

00:45:14.041 --> 00:45:16.690
the year 2000,2001 actually.
 

00:45:16.690 --> 00:45:21.510
The jets that we're trying to
catch up to on the September 11,

00:45:21.510 --> 00:45:25.916
2001, hijackers,
they were scuttled from the

00:45:25.916 --> 00:45:30.940
Massachusetts military
reservation on Cape Cod.

00:45:30.940 --> 00:45:36.170
This site is sitting on sands
and gravels.

00:45:36.170 --> 00:45:41.416
And it's basically a collection
of very large aquifers on Cape

00:45:41.416 --> 00:45:44.257
Cod,
in which the freshwater sits on

00:45:44.257 --> 00:45:48.659
top of underlying saltwater the
closer you get to the ocean.

00:45:48.659 --> 00:45:52.364
So that anything put on the
surface will drain into

00:45:52.364 --> 00:45:56.219
underlying sands and aquifers
moving very quickly.

00:45:56.219 --> 00:46:00.353
So this has become the largest
drinking water contamination

00:46:00.353 --> 00:46:04.130
site and remediation site in the
United States now.

00:46:04.130 --> 00:46:08.367
They drilled some 8,000
different wells to try to figure

00:46:08.367 --> 00:46:11.820
out where the fuels,
the flame retardants,

00:46:11.820 --> 00:46:15.144
the munitions residues,
the TNT and RDX,

00:46:15.144 --> 00:46:17.050
etc., where did it go?
 

00:46:17.050 --> 00:46:20.253
And they've monitored it out,
and they created these plumes

00:46:20.253 --> 00:46:23.179
that pump the water up,
out of that aquifer and then

00:46:23.179 --> 00:46:26.405
into these charcoal tanks,
activated carbon tanks,

00:46:26.405 --> 00:46:30.630
some of which are bigger than
this entire lecture hall.

00:46:30.630 --> 00:46:34.900
So day after day,
twenty-four hours a day,

00:46:34.900 --> 00:46:37.652
decade for decade,
this water is pumping through

00:46:37.652 --> 00:46:40.177
there,
hoping that it will be cleaned

00:46:40.177 --> 00:46:44.106
up to meet the Safe Drinking
Water Act standards by the year

00:46:44.106 --> 00:46:44.639
2035.
 

00:46:44.639 --> 00:46:48.432
Three thousand pounds of
solvents have been removed from

00:46:48.432 --> 00:46:49.329
that water.
 

00:46:49.329 --> 00:46:51.713
One thousand pounds of fuels
was removed from the

00:46:51.713 --> 00:46:52.409
groundwater.
 

00:46:52.409 --> 00:46:54.994
And eight plumes are now
undergoing treatment and

00:46:54.994 --> 00:46:55.750
remediation.
 

00:46:55.750 --> 00:46:59.735
This is immediately adjacent to
a variety of cranberry bogs,

00:46:59.735 --> 00:47:03.856
so cranberry farmers bore the
brunt of economic loss when this

00:47:03.856 --> 00:47:05.139
was discovered.
 

00:47:05.139 --> 00:47:09.192
So critical lessons here about
Vieques, knowledge is power,

00:47:09.192 --> 00:47:10.590
that's very clear.
 

00:47:10.590 --> 00:47:14.539
Classified information prevents
the public from understanding

00:47:14.539 --> 00:47:16.420
what was done,
when and where,

00:47:16.420 --> 00:47:19.311
what the nature of surrounding
or nearby community threats

00:47:19.311 --> 00:47:19.920
might be.
 

00:47:19.920 --> 00:47:22.260
A question of who conducts the
science.

00:47:22.260 --> 00:47:25.425
It's clear that the ATSDR who
are within the Centers from

00:47:25.425 --> 00:47:29.121
Disease Control,
was not doing high quality

00:47:29.121 --> 00:47:35.375
science and came to a premature
conclusion of safety based upon

00:47:35.375 --> 00:47:38.300
a highly limited sampling.
 

00:47:38.300 --> 00:47:41.639
Science normally proves no
causal relation.

00:47:41.639 --> 00:47:45.956
So this type of science is
perhaps one of the more complex

00:47:45.956 --> 00:47:47.699
that I could imagine.
 

00:47:47.699 --> 00:47:52.538
Also one lesson here that is
apparent is that new evidence of

00:47:52.538 --> 00:47:57.458
risky behavior generates a very
defensive attitude on the part

00:47:57.458 --> 00:47:58.909
of government.
 

00:47:58.909 --> 00:48:02.795
So any information that they
release, any studies that they

00:48:02.795 --> 00:48:05.610
conduct, could increase their
liability.

00:48:05.610 --> 00:48:09.811
So often the response is
"Well, then let's just not

00:48:09.811 --> 00:48:11.110
study it."
 

00:48:11.110 --> 00:48:12.768
Okay.
 

00:48:12.768 --> 00:48:14.378
I'm going to pause there,
and just wish you a great

00:48:14.378 --> 00:48:14.699
weekend.
 

